- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: macOS 10.12.1

#### Steps to Reproduce:

1. Save the following as `test.css`:

```css
body {
  --my-theme: {
    color: red;
    background: white;
  };
}

body div {
  @apply --my-theme;
}
```

2. Open it in VSCode, observe syntax errors.

#### More context

The new css features are really nice, a significant improvement in most development workflows. However, there is some legal CSS syntax (like css custom property values) that is flagged as a syntax error, and there are some emerging CSS features (like `@apply`) that extend the standard CSS grammar.

I'm on the Polymer team at Google, and we've recently shipped early versions of a language server and a plugin for VSCode to provide a high quality developer experience to our users. I've filed https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-css-languageservice/issues/7 and https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-css-languageservice/issues/8 but in the meantime is there anything our users can do – or that we can do in our plugin – to reduce the disruptiveness of these syntax errors to their development experience?

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1 `02611b40b24c9df2726ad8b33f5ef5f67ac30b44` 2016-11-03T13:44:00.572Z
- OS Version: OSX 10.12.1 (16B2657)

## Issue

The whitespace on the LHS of a destructuring assignment is not formatted.

## Steps to Reproduce:

1. Add the following to a typescript file:

```JS
const {NoSpaces} = { NoSpaces: 1 }
const { WithSpaces } = { WithSpaces: 1 }
const {OneSpace } = { OneSpace: 1 };
```

2. Format the document.

## Expected

I would expect the whitespace on the LHS of the assignment to be consistent. I would expect either:

```JS
const {NoSpaces} = { NoSpaces: 1 }
const {WithSpaces} = { WithSpaces: 1 }
const {OneSpace} = { OneSpace: 1 };
```

or 

```JS
const { NoSpaces } = { NoSpaces: 1 }
const { WithSpaces } = { WithSpaces: 1 }
const { OneSpace } = { OneSpace: 1 };
```

## Actual Output

Whitespace of the LHS is inconsistent:

```JS
const {NoSpaces} = { NoSpaces: 1 }
const { WithSpaces } = { WithSpaces: 1 }
const {OneSpace } = { OneSpace: 1 };
```

